#### Feature Description

Inputmode="numeric" works as intended everywhere. Except that on a browser, if anyone tries to type text into a input with inputmode="numeric", that is allowed. On android, this is offset by the fact that the qwerty keyboard is not shown, only the numeric keyboard is shown.

I use the following directive right now, but I would like to have it included in angular as a 'default' behaviour

```
@Directive({
    selector: 'input[inputmode=numeric]'
})
export class StringNumberDirective {
    constructor(private el: ElementRef<HTMLInputElement>) {
    }
    get input(): HTMLInputElement {
        return this.el.nativeElement
    }

    @HostListener('input') onInput() {
        const re: RegExp = new RegExp('[^0-9]');
        this.input.value = this.input.value.replace(re, '');
    }
}
```

#### Use Case
Every data model that requires a number as a string, instead of a quantity. For example numeric roll numbers for an exam, or telephone number without dashes. 
Also, if you need to have a max-length (not max-value. Ex: string roll number number with max 10 digits) for the numerical string, that won't work with 'type=number', because html type=number does not support the max-length attribute. 
However, using this directive with max-length helps natively have a string number with a limited size
